ources of the Morte Darthur, evaluating the case for them to see what conclusions may be drawn of Malory's life, work, and mental furnishings. In so doing, it clarifies the process by which Malory created his work. It shows that Malory carried an eclectic body of literature in his mind and worked at least partly from memory; and it illuminates his interest in characters of his own social class, the breadth of his enthusiasm for Arthurian literature, and the depth of his commitment to provide his countrymen with "the hoole book of kyng Arthur and of his noble knyghtes of the Round Table". RALPH NORRIS teaches in the Department of English at Kennesaw State University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArthurian romancesxHistory and criticism. 0aArthurian romancesxSources. 4aBibliography & Manuscripts. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aREFERENCE / Bibliographies & Indexes.2bisacsh  aArthurian literature.  aMalory.  aMorte Darthur.  aRound Table.  aauthor.  achivalry.  acreation.  aliterature.  amedieval literature.  anoble knights.  asources.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846156595423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846156595/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles